<div class="functional wob">
  <div class="wrapper">
    <article>
      <h1>Functional</h1>
      <p>
        It was important that the CAD file was more than just an appearance model.
        With this in mind, I referenced the goggles I owned,
        along with images and models I found online.
      </p>
    </article>
    <figure></figure>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="visualization text-image-layout image-last bow">
  <div class="wrapper">
    <figure class="slide-container">
      <img class="slide" src="images/goggles-sketch3.png" alt="sketch3" />
      <img class="slide" src="images/goggles-sketch2.png" alt="sketch2" />
      <img class="slide" src="images/goggles-sketch1.png" alt="sketch1" />
    </figure>
    <article>
      <h1>Visualization</h1>
      <h3>Developing Aesthetic</h3>
      <p>
        I couldn’t articulate the surface transitions I needed sketching in 3D.
        By working through the front profile,
        I developed my intended aesthetic.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="framework text-image-layout image-first bow">
  <div class="wrapper">
    <figure><img src="images/goggles-framework.png" alt="framework" /></figure>
    <article>
      <h1>Framework</h1>
      <h3>So far, so good</h3>
      <p>
        I was able to build an accurate frame and lens to serve as my guide to design around.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="setback text-image-layout image-last bow">
  <div class="wrapper">
    <figure><img src="images/goggles-setback.png" alt="setback" /></figure>
    <article>
      <h1>Setback</h1>
      <h3>Time to restart</h3>
      <p>
        I spent weeks modeling in circles trying to define my surfaces in SolidWorks.
        As my file grew I realized my surfaces were not lining up,
        and I was not getting the aesthetic I desired.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="new-direction slanted-top text-image-layout image-first wob">
  <div class="wrapper">
    <figure><img src="images/goggles-new-direction.png" alt="new-direction" /></figure>
    <article>
      <h1>New Direction</h1>
      <h3>Making it printable</h3>
      <p>
        After adding supports to the correct part of my CAD file and printed it to serve as my guide.
        I would then be able to sculpt the surfaces I needed on top of this print.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="designed-in-3d text-image-layout image-last wob">
  <div class="wrapper">
    <figure><img src="images/goggles-printed.png" alt="new-direction" /></figure>
    <article>
      <h1>Designed in 3D</h1>
      <p>
        With this printed structure for reference,
        I was able to design and itterate until I had a desirable aesthetic.
        This step of the process was crutial to figuring our how these surfaces transitioned between one another.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="back-to-digital slanted-bottom text-image-layout image-first wob">
  <div class="wrapper">
    <figure><img src="images/goggles-scanner.png" alt="new-direction" /></figure>
    <article>
      <h1>Back to digital</h1>
      <h3>Scanned in model</h3>
      <p>
        Our department had just aquired a 3D scanner and I worked with the school to get the equiptment working.
        After scores of lost hours learning,
        I finally had a water tight scan set up in SolidWorks and was ready to start modeling.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
